name: Dan Hurley
summary: The Los Angeles Lakers attempted to lure Dan Hurley away from UConn with a substantial offer, but Hurley ultimately rejected the NBA team to remain with the Huskies. The Lakers were reportedly interested in hiring Hurley as their next head coach, but he declined their six-year, $70 million contract proposal. Hurley's decision to stay at UConn came after speculation that his departure would create a "nightmare" scenario for the Huskies. UConn has won two consecutive NCAA titles under Hurley's leadership, and he is determined to pursue a third straight championship with the program. The Lakers' search for a new coach continues, while UConn can breathe a sigh of relief as they retain their successful coach.

name: Rebecca Grossman
summary: Rebecca Grossman, a California socialite, has been sentenced to 15 years to life in prison for killing two young boys in a crosswalk in Los Angeles. The incident, which occurred in 2020, sparked outrage and a request for a 34-year sentence from the district attorney. Grossman, who co-founded a burn foundation, initially faced charges of murder and gross vehicular manslaughter. Despite her defense attorney's argument for a new trial, the judge denied the request, and Grossman was sentenced to 15 years to life in prison. The case has been widely reported by various news outlets, including the Los Angeles Times, NBC Los Angeles, FOX 11 Los Angeles, TIME, Courthouse News Service, VC Star, NBC News, The Washington Post, KABC-TV, and KTLA Los Angeles.

summary: Tony Evans, the senior pastor of Oak Cliff Bible Fellowship Church, has announced that he is stepping down from his pastoral duties due to a past sin that he has acknowledged. Evans has stated that he is taking this step to prioritize his repentance and restoration. He believes that this is the right thing to do for himself, his family, his church, and the broader Christian community. During his time away, Evans will not be involved in any public ministry or teaching activities. He has asked for prayers and support from his congregation and the Christian community during this time of transition.
